{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638200"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17696"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17696"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73232"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10410"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17696"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58703"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10406"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25007"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73232"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe olfactory system has unique anatomical features that distinguish it from other sensory systems in the human body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary neural pathway for olfactory information?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Olfactory receptors to olfactory bulb to primary olfactory cortex","Olfactory receptors to thalamus to cortex","Olfactory receptors to hypothalamus to limbic system","Olfactory receptors to brainstem to thalamus","Olfactory receptors to trigeminal nerve to cortex"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct pathway is \u003Cstrong\u003Eolfactory receptors to olfactory bulb to primary olfactory cortex\u003C/strong\u003E. Olfactory receptor neurons in the nasal epithelium send axons through the cribriform plate to synapse with mitral cells in the olfactory bulb. These mitral cells then project directly to the primary olfactory cortex without thalamic relay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other pathways described are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlfactory receptors to thalamus to cortex\u003C/strong\u003E represents the typical sensory pathway seen in other systems like vision and hearing, but olfaction is unique in bypassing the thalamus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlfactory receptors to hypothalamus to limbic system\u003C/strong\u003E describes secondary connections of the olfactory system but not the primary sensory pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlfactory receptors to brainstem to thalamus\u003C/strong\u003E describes a pathway more typical of the vestibular system\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlfactory receptors to trigeminal nerve to cortex\u003C/strong\u003E confuses the separate chemosensory function of the trigeminal nerve with true olfaction\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe olfactory system is unique among sensory systems as it is the only one that bypasses thalamic relay before reaching the cortex. This direct pathway reflects its evolutionary age and importance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The olfactory receptor neurons in the nasal epithelium synapse directly with mitral cells in the olfactory bulb.","Olfactory information travels from the olfactory bulb to the primary olfactory cortex without first passing through the thalamus.","The olfactory system is unique among sensory systems as it bypasses thalamic relay."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58703"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17696"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58703"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T09:32:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T09:33:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10410"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73232"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://ap